<h2>Maine Incentives & Rebates</h2>
<p>Maine offers some of the most comprehensive incentive programs in New England for both solar and HVAC investments. The federal Investment Tax Credit (ITC) provides a 30% tax credit for solar installations completed through 2032, with the credit stepping down to 26% in 2033 and 22% in 2034. This credit applies to the total cost of solar equipment and installation, making it one of the most valuable incentives available to Maine homeowners.</p>

<p>The state of Maine provides additional solar rebates through the Solar and Wind Rebate Program, offering up to \$4,000 in rebates for residential solar installations. This program provides \$1.00 per watt for the first 2,000 watts and \$0.50 per watt for the next 4,000 watts, with higher rebates available for certain solar panel types manufactured in the United States. Maine also exempts solar installations from sales tax and provides a property tax exemption for the added value of solar systems.</p>

<p>Central Maine Power offers the Heat Pump Rebate Program, providing rebates up to \$1,500 for qualifying cold-climate heat pumps and up to \$1,000 for ductless mini-split systems. The utility also provides additional incentives for heat pump water heaters and smart thermostats. Efficiency Maine, the state's energy efficiency administrator, offers comprehensive rebates for insulation, air sealing, and high-efficiency heating systems. Low-income households may qualify for enhanced rebates and financing programs through Efficiency Maine's Home Energy Savings Program.</p>

<p>Net metering in Maine allows solar system owners to receive credit for excess electricity they generate and feed back into the grid. The state's net metering policy provides credit at the full retail rate for systems up to 660kW, making solar installations more economically attractive. Additionally, Maine offers property tax exemptions for renewable energy systems and sales tax exemptions for solar equipment purchases.</p>

